-- Ayala, CSL, Formosa, Goodman, HSBC, Posco: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview
-- Ian C. Sayson
-- 2010-06-17T21:40:12Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-17/ayala-csl-formosa-goodman-hsbc-posco-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  Asian trading , excluding Japan. Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  
 Ayala Corp.  (AC PM): The owner of the largest Philippine
builder acquired 122,430 of its own shares at 312.50 pesos and
315 pesos each, a stock-exchange filing showed. The stock fell
0.8 percent to 317.50 pesos.  
 CSL Ltd.  (CSL AU): The world’s second-largest maker of
blood-based treatments agreed to supply plasma-based products to
ProFibrix B.V. to produce Fibrocaps to stop bleeding during or
after surgery. The Leiden, Netherlands-based company made the
announcement in a PR Newswire statement. The stock rose 0.2
percent to A$33.38.  
 Formosa Petrochemical Corp.  (6505 TT): Taiwan’s only
publicly traded petroleum refiner plans to expand its crude oil
processing capacity to 593,000 barrels a day in three years,
Chairman Wilfred Wang said. The stock climbed 1.6 percent to
NT$82.50.  
 Goodman Fielder Ltd.  (GFF AU): Australia’s largest baker
raised $300 million through the sale of 10-year unsecured notes
to repay bank debt due later this year. The money will be
converted to Australian dollars with the principal, interest and
final repayments hedged to the domestic currency, a stock-
exchange filing showed. Goodman’s stock rose 2.2 percent A$1.405.  
 HSBC Holdings Plc  (5 HK): Europe’s largest bank may raise
as much as $10 billion by selling new shares in Shanghai next
year, Matrix Corporate Capital LLP analyst  Andrew Lim  said. The
increase in capital would boost the bank’s Core Tier 1 ratio, a
measure of financial strength, to 7.3 percent at the end of 2012,
which is “more in line with its peers,” he said. The stock
gained 0.2 percent to HK$74.05.  
 Hynix Semiconductor Inc.  (000660 KS): An investor has
offered to sell 4.41 million shares in the world’s No. 2
computer memory chipmaker at 28,200 won each in a block deal,
Reuters reported, citing an unidentified person. Goldman Sachs
Group Inc. and Daewoo Securities Co. are arranging the sale of
the stake, worth about $103 million at yesterday’s closing price,
according to the report. The stock increased 3.3 percent to
28,200 won.  
 Posco  (005490 KS): South Korea’s largest steelmaker may
invest about 1 trillion won ($820 million) to build a plant
based on Finex technology and with annual capacity of 2 million
metric tons, the Korea Economic Daily reported, citing
unidentified industry officials. The stock declined 0.1 percent
to 471,500 won.  
 PT Perusahaan Gas Negara  (PGAS IJ): Shareholders approved a
dividend payout of 60 percent of last year’s net profit, Finance
Director  Riza Pahlevi Tabrani  said. Gas Negara, Indonesia’s
biggest gas distributor, rose 1.3 percent to 3,925 rupiah.  
 SK Energy Co.  (096770 KS): A naphtha cracker owned by South
Korea’s biggest oil refiner shut down because of a power failure,
a company official said yesterday. Power failed at the plant
around 11:45 a.m. local time, said the official, who asked not
to be identified because of company rules. The stock fell 2.8
percent to 104,500 won.  
 Telstra Corp Ltd.  (TLS AU): Australia’s largest phone
company, sold A$150 million ($129 million) of 10-year bonds in
its first domestic debt issue since 2006. The 7.75 percent notes
were priced to yield 200 basis points more than the 10-year swap
rate, sale manager National Australia Bank Ltd. said. The stock
fell 0.6 percent to A$3.16.  
